{{Infobox academic | name = Gillian Clark | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA|size=100%}} | image = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | nationality = British | other_names = Edith Gillian Clark | spouse = [[Stephen R.&nbsp;L. Clark]] | awards = <!--notable national level awards only--> | alma_mater = [[Somerville College, Oxford]] | thesis_title = Augustus and the Historians<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Clark |first=Edith Gillian |year=1974 |title=Augustus and the Historians |type=DPhil dissertation |location=Oxford |publisher=University of Oxford |oclc=43092152}}</ref> | thesis_year = 1973 | school_tradition = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | influences = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | era = | discipline = {{hlist | Classics | history}} | sub_discipline = <!--academic discipline specialist area – e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist--> | workplaces = [[University of Bristol]] | doctoral_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | notable_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = [[Late antiquity]] | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | signature = | signature_alt = }} '''Edith Gillian Clark''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA}} is Emeritus Professor of Classics and Ancient History at the [[University of Bristol]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://research-information.bristol.ac.uk/en/persons/e-g-clark(0cbe03de-bbd5-4dc1-82d4-6ea06a414354).html|title=Professor Gillian Clark|website=research-information.bristol.ac.uk|access-date=3 July 2016}}</ref> She retired from the University of Bristol in 2010. Clark has made a significant contribution to the history, literature, and religion of [[late antiquity]].{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} She is currently{{as of when|date=September 2018}} working on a commentary of [[Augustine of Hippo]]'s ''[[The City of God (book)|City of God]]'', under contract with [[Oxford University Press]]. She is a [[Fellow of the British Academy]] and an editor for the ''Translated Texts for Historians'' ''300–800'' series, published by [[Liverpool University Press]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://liverpooluniversitypress.co.uk/collections/series-translated-texts-for-historians|title=series-Translated-Texts-For-Historians|publisher=Liverpool University Press|access-date=3 July 2016}}</ref> She is editor of the monograph series ''Oxford Early Christian Texts'', published by Oxford University Press. An event, "Christianity and Roman Society: A Colloquium for Professor Gillian Clark", was held in her honour in 2011 at the University of Bristol and a ''festschrift'' was published in 2014 as a result.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/classics/news/2011/34.html|title=Christianity and Roman Society: A colloquium for Professor Gillian Clark, Bristol University|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>
Clark studied Greek and Latin language and literature, ancient history, and philosophy at [[Somerville College, Oxford]]. She received her [[Master of Arts]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degrees from the [[University of Oxford]]. She has taught at the universities of Glasgow, St Andrews, Manchester, Liverpool and Bristol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/users/professor-gillian-clark|title=Professor Gillian Clark|publisher=British Academy|access-date=3 July 2016}}</ref>
