'''Hlonipha Mokoena''' is a South African historian at the Wits Institute for Social and Economic Research of the [[University of the Witwatersrand]]. She is a specialist is South African intellectual history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.socialdifference.columbia.edu/faculty-/hlonipha-mokoena|title=Hlonipha Mokoena|website=Socialdifference.columbia.edu|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> She formerly worked in the anthropology department at Columbia University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiser.wits.ac.za/users/hlonipha-mokoena|title=Hlonipha Mokoena - Wits Institute for Social and Economic Research|website=Wiser.wits.ac.za|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> She received her PhD from the University of Cape Town in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/hlonipha-mokoena-296367|title=Hlonipha Mokoena|website=The Conversation|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> Her book, ''Magema Fuze: The Making of a Kholwa Intellectual'', is about [[Magema Magwaza Fuze]], the first Zulu-speaker to publish a book in the language.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackportraitures.info/speakers/hlonipha-mokoena/|title=Hlonipha Mokoena «  Black Portraiture[s] Conferences|website=Blackportraitures.info|accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02590123.2012.11964180|title=Hlonipha Mokoena. Magema Fuze: The Making of a Kholwa Intellectual. Moss Mashamaite, The Second Coming: The Life and Times of Pixley ka Isaka Seme, The Founder of the ANC|first1=T.J.|last1=Tallie|first2=Scott|last2=Couper|date=1 January 2012|publisher=|journal=Journal of Natal and Zulu History|volume=30|issue=1|pages=101–106|accessdate=14 August 2018|doi=10.1080/02590123.2012.11964180}}</ref>

