[[File:Clapham - Machines and national rivalries, 1938 - 5852721.tif|thumb|''Machines and National Rivalries (1887-1914)'', 1938 [https://archive.org/details/economichistoryo00clap online edition]]]
Professor '''Sir John Harold Clapham''', CBE, LittD, FBA (13 September 1873 – 29 March 1946) was a British economic historian.

He was educated at [[The Leys School]] in Cambridge and [[King's College, Cambridge]]. From 1889 to 1902 he was a lecturer in History and Economics at [[Leeds University]] and was Professor of Economics there from 1902 to 1908.<ref>{{acad|id=CLFN892JH|name=Clapham, John Harold}}</ref> He was the first Professor of Economic History at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]] from 1928 to 1938, and Vice-Provost of [[King's College, Cambridge]] from 1933 until 1943 when he received a [[knighthood]].

Between 1926 and 1938 he published, in three volumes, ''An Economic History of Modern Britain''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/makinghistory/historians/clapham_john.html |title=Clapham, John - Historian Profiles - Making History |publisher=History.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JBqWbDmFsfEC&pg=PA232&lpg=PA231 |title=Encyclopedia of Historians and Historical Writing - Kelly Boyd - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref> He is also recognised for his study of the [[Industrial Revolution]] in England, and for describing cooperatives in the initiation of the revolution.  He is also remembered for his 1944 ''The Bank of England, A History''.<ref>Clapham, J. (1944) ''The Bank of England, A History'' (2 Vols), Cambridge: [[Cambridge University Press]], {{ISBN|0-521-04662-9}}</ref>

Welsh economic historian Sir [[John Habakkuk]] was one of his students.<ref>[[F. M. L. Thompson]], [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sir-john-habakkuk-603942.html, obituary, ''The Independent'' (11 November 2002)]</ref> One of Clapham's more notable quotations is: "Economic advance is not the same thing as human progress".{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

