[[File:Sabinin. Glory of Iveria.jpg|thumb|"The Glory of [[Caucasian Iberia|Iveria]]" by M. Sabinin remains one of the most revered Georgian Orthodox icons to this day.]] '''Mikhail (Gobron) Sabinin''' ({{lang-ka|მიხეილ [გობრონ] საბინინი}}, {{lang-ru|Михаил Павлович [Геброн] Сабинин}}) (1845–1900) was a [[Russia|Russo]]-[[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] monk, historian of the [[Georgian Orthodox Church]] and [[icon]] painter.
He was born to the Russian priest from [[Tver]], Pavel Sabinin, and a Georgian woman. Educated at the [[Tiflis]] gymnasium in the 1860s, he then attended [[St. Petersburg Theologian Academy]] and attained to a [[Magister (degree)|magister degree]] for his work ''History of the Georgian Church until the End of the 6th Century'' ("История грузинской церкви до конца VI в." [СПб., 1877]), the first comprehensive treatment of the subject produced in Russian. He travelled in several regions of Georgia, studying monuments of Christian architecture, copying frescos and icons, recording legends and collecting manuscripts. In St. Petersburg, he was tonsured a monk and given the name Gobron after a 10th-century [[Gobron|Georgian saint]]. In 1882, he published ''The Paradise of Georgia'' (საქართველოს სამოთხე; St. Petersburg, 1882), a voluminous lithographed edition of biographies of important Georgian Orthodox Christian saints. In the 1880s, he served at the famous [[Iviron Monastery]] on [[Mount Athos]]. In 1882 he published also ''[[Eustathius of Mtskheta|The Passion of Eustathius of Mtskheta]]''.
In 1898, he clashed with the office of [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian]] [[exarchate]] at Tiflis over his criticism of [[Russification]] and was removed from Georgia to [[Moscow]] where he died of [[pneumonia]] on May 10, 1900.<ref>{{ru icon}} [http://www.pravoslavie.ru/cgi-bin/sykon/client/display.pl?sid=374&did=1079 Важа Кикнадзе. Михаил Сабинин – подвижник Грузинской Церкви] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013160659/http://www.pravoslavie.ru/cgi-bin/sykon/client/display.pl?sid=374&did=1079 |date=2007-10-13 }}. ''Pravoslavie.Ru''. Accessed on September 3, 2007.</ref>
